# === GENERAL CONVENTIONS ===
- Use modern JavaScript (ES6+). Avoid TypeScript.
- Always use named exports. Avoid default exports.
- Prefer small, focused files and components.
- Follow the Single Responsibility Principle throughout the codebase.

# === REACT ===
- Use function components only. Never use class components.
- If the file exceeds 400 lines, consider splitting into multiple files logically.
- Avoid `useEffect` when possible. Use `useMemo`, `useCallback` appropriately.
- Reorganize any given React component to follow this structure:
1. Constants and variables not dependent on state, props, or hooks.
2. State and refs (`useState`, `useReducer`, `useRef`).
3. Other hooks (`useEffect`, `useMemo`, `useCallback`, `useContext`, etc.).
4. Internal helper functions that are not event handlers.
5. Event handler functions (`onClick`, `onChange`, etc.).
6. JSX return at the end, with minimal inline logic. 
Extract complex logic to helpers or subcomponents.
Keep formatting clean, code readable, and maintain existing functionality.

- No direct DOM manipulation – use declarative JSX only.
- Use dynamic imports for non-critical or heavy components.

# === NEXT.JS =====
- Follow Next.js routing and file-based convention strictly.

# === STYLING (TAILWIND CSS + SHADCN) ===
<!-- - Use Tailwind CSS only. No inline styles unless necessary. -->
<!-- - Use shadcn/ui components when available. -->
<!-- - Always write mobile-first and responsive layouts. -->
- Keep design consistent using spacing, font sizes, and color utilities.
- Avoid hardcoded colors. Use predefined classes or variables.

# === API ROUTES ===
- API input must be validated using Zod.
- Return a unified API response structure:
  {
    success: boolean,
    data: any,
    error: null | { message, code }
  }
- No raw SQL queries. Use Prisma for all DB operations.
- No logic inside route handlers – move it to services or controllers.

# === PRISMA + POSTGRESQL ===
- Each Prisma model should represent a single entity (SRP).
- Use relation fields with explicit naming.
- Migrations should be tracked and described in `CHANGELOG.md`.
- No cascade delete without business justification.
- Use Prisma Client methods only – no `executeRaw` unless safe and validated.

# === UTILS & SERVICES ===
- Reusable logic belongs in `lib/`, `utils/`, or `services/`.
- Utility functions must be pure and testable.
- Use `function` keyword for shared utility functions, not arrow functions.

# === FOLDER STRUCTURE ===
- No more than one `index.js` per folder.
- Separate concerns: UI, data, routing, logic.
- Components live in `components/`; logic lives in `lib/` or `services/`.

# === NAMING & CODE STYLE ===
- camelCase for JS variables and functions.
- PascalCase for components.
- snake_case for database fields.
- Use clear, descriptive names: e.g. isLoading, handleSubmit, formData.

# === PERFORMANCE ===
- Use lazy loading for images and non-critical assets.
- Optimize image formats (.webp) and add width/height attributes.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders. Use memoization when needed.
- Minimize use of useState/useEffect in favor of server components where possible.
<!-- 
# === TESTING ===
- Use @testing-library/react for all UI tests.
- Test business logic separately from UI.
- No untested API routes. -->

# === DOCUMENTATION ===
- Each public function, utility, or API route must include a comment describing input/output.
- Maintain README.md per module when logic is complex or shared.
- Do not add explanatory comments when modifying existing code unless the comment is strictly necessary to clarify complex or non-obvious logic.


